{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17488656","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17488656"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T03:51:11+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T03:51:11+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"503"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"503","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/503"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.28,0.41,0.12,0.16,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"503"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"106206"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"503","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/503"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"503"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"88674"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"8"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"430"},{"type":"tags","id":"2076"},{"type":"tags","id":"4963"},{"type":"tags","id":"4977"},{"type":"tags","id":"11626"},{"type":"tags","id":"11636"},{"type":"tags","id":"12920"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"4711"},{"type":"contributions","id":"4719"},{"type":"contributions","id":"7251"},{"type":"contributions","id":"32941"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39103"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43963"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"106206","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/106206"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 74-year-old woman with type II diabetes presents for a regular eye check up to her GP. She does not have any issues with watching the television, although has noted some constriction in her peripheral vision when driving. On examination, her visual acuity is 6/6 in both eyes. On fundoscopy, the following is seen (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one the following is the most likely explanation for her symptoms?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Age-related macular degeneration","Primary open-angle glaucoma","Hypertensive retinopathy","Papilloedema","Optic neuritis"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with a constriction of her peripheral visual field, along with a fundoscopy demonstrating a high cup:disc ratio of the optic disc. There are some misleading light artefacts in the photograph. There is no A-V nipping (there should be consistent 90\u003Csup\u003Eo\u003C/sup\u003E crossing of arterioles over veins plus venular narrowing each side of the arterioles). Inferiorly the light area next to the arteriole is probably in the choroid and not on the wall.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis is consistent with \u003Cstrong\u003EPrimary open-angle glaucoma\u003C/strong\u003E. Notably, her visual acuity is normal bilaterally as her central vision has not been affected. The optic disc is the area of the retina in which the retinal nerve fiber layers bundle together and exit to the brain. The optic disc normally has a central portion called the \u0027cup\u0027, which is smaller than the disc. In patients with glaucoma, there is a death of the retinal nerve fibers and this causes an increase in the cup:disc ratio. A normal cup:disc ratio is 0.3 with a ratio of less than 0.5 being considered normal.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPatients with \u003Cstrong\u003Eage-related macular degeneration\u003C/strong\u003E are often asymptomatic with normal vision. They can present with visual distortions (metamorphopsia). On fundoscopic exam, drusen will be seen. This is not observed in this patient.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis patient does not have a history of hypertension and so \u003Cstrong\u003Ehypertensive retinopathy\u003C/strong\u003E is less likely. No signs of hypertensive retinopathy are seen on fundoscopic exam such as AV-nicking, silver or copper wiring.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPapilloedema\u003C/strong\u003E is seen as a swelling of the optic discs bilaterally and is secondary to increased intracranial pressure. This is not seen here.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOptic neuritis\u003C/strong\u003E usually affects the posterior nerve and will present with signs of impaired optic nerve function (decreased visual acuity, decreased colour vision, relative afferent pupillary defect, central scotoma) and a fundoscopic examination will show disc hyperaemia and swelling in children, but the commoner adult optic neuritis posterior nerve so the disc looks normal.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Primary open-angle glaucoma is often detected incidentally and many patients are asymptomatic","A high cup:disc ratio along with a constriction of the peripheral visual fields is consistent with primary open-angle glaucoma."],"references":["Stein JD, Khawaja AP, Weizer JS. Glaucoma in Adults-Screening, Diagnosis, and Management: A Review. JAMA. 2021 Jan 12;325(2):164-174. doi: 10.1001 Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/33433580/","Wagner IV, Stewart MW, Dorairaj SK. Updates on the Diagnosis and Management of Glaucoma. Mayo Clin Proc Innov Qual Outcomes. 2022 Nov 16;6(6):618-635. doi: 10.1016/j.mayocpiqo.2022.09.007. PMID: 36405987; PMCID: PMC9673042. Available from: https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC9673042/","Dietze J, Blair K, Zeppieri M, et al. Glaucoma. [Updated 2024 Mar 16]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2025 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK538217/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"88674"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"503"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"17573"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"17573","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/17573"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/8b0b25e8-db8f-4220-881a-c21c2127d359.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/8b0b25e8-db8f-4220-881a-c21c2127d359.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":527,"height":440}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"88674","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/88674"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-06-16T19:49:00+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-06-16T19:49:56+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"503"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"106206"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"8","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/8"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc41","name":"Ophthalmology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72